    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1879-11-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1879-11-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="633" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d633">
                <head>No. 633.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Farman</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Payson</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Consulate-General of the United States in
                                        Egypt</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>,
                                    <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-11-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 28, 1879</date>. (Received December
                                17.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 352.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: You will remember, when I had the pleasure
                            of seeing you last, that I mentioned that the United States bad no
                            prison in Egypt, and desired to know in what prison any person that
                            should be sentenced by the United States consular court in Egypt to
                            imprisonment for a term of years, could be confined.</p>
                <p>Will you please give me instructions in this respect? I should like also
                            to be informed as to whether or not the prison for such purpose has
                            facilities for providing the convicts with labor, so that they can be
                            sentenced to “hard labor” as well as confinement.</p>
                <p>I would thank you to send me an answer to this by the first mail.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>E. E. FARMAN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
